nodes.body: I'm thinking maybe we should just upgrade [finEquivZmultiples](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/GroupTheory/OrderOfElement.html#finEquivZmultiples) to an AddMonoidHom ... (when the order is infinite (0) it's [Int.castAddHom](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Int/Cast/Lemmas.html#Int.castAddHom)). It's certainly nice to have a computable (in the forward direction) version that takes an arbitrary element, not an arbitrarily chosen generator. We can then specialize it to the cyclic case. Also, there are currently several `hcard â–¸` that will prevent the terms from reducing, and we may want to introduce a `ZMod.castRingEquiv` similar to [Fin.cast](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Std/Data/Fin/Basic.html#Fin.cast) to get around the problem. I'm suggesting this because if we're gonna do finite group theory more heavily we probably want the Lean kernel to help checking computations.

I'm also quite interested in the computational possibilities in the future.
I started doing something for the latest suggestion, but I was not able to make my `zmodZmultiplesHom` function computable because `addOrderOf` and `orderOf` are noncomputable!

since this is data:
```suggestion
    Multiplicative G â§¸ zpowers (Multiplicative.ofAdd g) â‰ƒ* Multiplicative (G â§¸ zmultiples g) :=
  MulEquiv.refl _
```

Please also add a lemma that says what `multiplicativeQuotientZpowersZmultiplesMulEquiv` applied to `QuotientGroup.mk` is, and similarly for `.symm`.

The former can be proved easily from the latter (after swapping the order):
```suggestion
/-- The isomorphism from `ZMod n` to any cyclic additive group of `Nat.card` equal to `n`. -/
noncomputable def zmodAddCyclicAddEquiv [AddGroup G] (h : IsAddCyclic G) :
    ZMod (Nat.card G) â‰ƒ+ G := by
  let n := Nat.card G
  let âŸ¨g, surjâŸ© := Classical.indefiniteDescription _ h.exists_generator
  have kereq : ((zmultiplesHom G) g).ker = zmultiples â†‘(Nat.card G) := by
    rw [zmultiplesHom_ker_eq]
    congr
    rw [â† Nat.card_zmultiples]
    exact Nat.card_congr (Equiv.subtypeUnivEquiv surj)
  exact (Int.quotientZmultiplesNatEquivZMod n)
    |>.symm.trans <| QuotientAddGroup.quotientAddEquivOfEq kereq
    |>.symm.trans <| QuotientAddGroup.quotientKerEquivOfSurjective (zmultiplesHom G g) surj

/-- The isomorphism from `Multiplicative (ZMod n)` to any cyclic group of `Nat.card` equal to `n`.
-/
noncomputable def zmodCyclicMulEquiv [Group G] (h : IsCyclic G) :
    Multiplicative (ZMod (Nat.card G)) â‰ƒ* G :=
  AddEquiv.toMultiplicative <| zmodAddCyclicAddEquiv <| isAddCyclic_additive_iff.2 h
```

This is defeq abuse, and suggests we're missing some lemmas about `Multiplicative`.

`simp_rw [â† ofAdd_zsmul]` helps a little here.
Just fixed this. Not sure if I'm still abusing the `divides = exists` defeq, but trying to type anything after the `conv_rhs` line naturally results in the error `no goals to be solved`.
Never mind, found a better solution.

`IsCyclic` and `IsAddCyclic` are type classes, so the arguments  can be changed to `[hG : IsCyclic G] [hH : IsCyclic H]` (and similarly for the additive version).

In the proof of `mulEquivOfPrimeCardEq` below, you can use `(hG := isCyclic_of_prime_card hG)` to specify the instance or use `have hGcyc := isCyclic_of_prime_card hG` (and similarly for `H`) before the `apply` and then leave them  out.

```suggestion
noncomputable def mulEquivOfCyclicCardEq [Group G] [Group H] [hG : IsCyclic G]
    [hH : IsCyclic H] (hcard : Nat.card G = Nat.card H) : G â‰ƒ* H := hcard â–¸
```

```suggestion
noncomputable def addEquivofAddCyclicCardEq [AddGroup G] [AddGroup H] [hG : IsAddCyclic G]
    [hH : IsAddCyclic H] (hcard : Nat.card G = Nat.card H) : G â‰ƒ+ H := hcard â–¸
```

```suggestion
  have hGcyc := isCyclic_of_prime_card hG
  have hHcyc := isCyclic_of_prime_card hH
  apply mulEquivOfCyclicCardEq
```

```suggestion
  have hGcyc := isAddCyclic_of_prime_card hG
  have hHcyc := isAddCyclic_of_prime_card hH
  apply addEquivofAddCyclicCardEq
```
Probably `@[to_additive]` can generate the additive versions of the last two statements automatically.

It seems like `@[to_additive]` has issues with everything in this section. For example:
```lean
/-
application type mismatch
  MonoidHom.ker
argument has type
  AddZeroClass G
but function has type
  [inst : MulOneClass G] â†’ (Multiplicative â„¤ â†’* G) â†’ Subgroup (Multiplicative â„¤)
-/
@[to_additive test]
theorem zpowersHom_ker_eq [Group G] (g : G) :
    (zpowersHom G g).ker = zpowers (Multiplicative.ofAdd â†‘(orderOf g)) := by
  ext n
  rw [MonoidHom.mem_ker, mem_zpowers_iff, zpowersHom_apply, â† orderOf_dvd_iff_zpow_eq_one]
  let m : â„¤ := n
  change _ âˆ£ m â†” âˆƒ k, k * (orderOf g : â„¤) = m
  conv in _ * _ = _ => rw [mul_comm, eq_comm]
```

Slight defeq abuse, but a much shorter proof is:
```suggestion
    (zpowersHom G g).ker = zpowers (Multiplicative.ofAdd â†‘(orderOf g)) :=
  congr_arg AddSubgroup.toSubgroup <| zmultiplesHom_ker_eq (Additive.ofMul g)
```
(after swapping the order again)

I think this one is probably ok, because it if does fail it's easy to fix by adding lemmas about the interaction between `ker` and `toSubgroup` etc.
I don't think these are actually supported by `toAdditive`, as their statements are not similar enough (one has `Multiplicative`). I'd suggest removing them.
All of them or just these two?
Oh I didn't see your earlier commit, so "all of them" and "just these two" are now synonymous.
So `zpowersHom` and `zmultiplesHom` involve `Multiplicative` and use `@[to_additive existing ...]`, which was my reason to add these.

I think that's just an error; I don't think `to_additive` ever actually succeeds for those definitions. The test of whether `attribute [to_additive] foo` is useful is whether you can write
```lean
@[to_additive]
def bar := someFunctionOf foo
```
and have everything work. I believe for these results that's not the case.
I see.
I'd be tempted to split these to a new PR: you're not using them, and the name possibly could do with some bikeshedding. It would also be nice to have the `Additive` versions.
Yeah, they used to be used in the proof of `zmodCyclicMulEquiv` but not anymore.

```suggestion
noncomputable def addEquivOfAddCyclicCardEq [AddGroup G] [AddGroup H] [hG : IsAddCyclic G]
```
